{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472185","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472185"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:55:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:55:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1084"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1084","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1084"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.27,0.12,0.51,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1084"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54452"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1084","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1084"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1084"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39961"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"631"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1442"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13869"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16577"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44041"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54452"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 17-year-old youth presents with a three week history of discomfort in the right side of his scrotum. He first noticed his symptoms after a game of football, during which he collided with an opponent and thought he may have been hurt in his scrotum. On examination the left side of the scrotum and contents are normal and on the right side there is a non-tender 8 cm swelling. The right testis cannot be clearly felt, but the cord appears normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following physical signs is most likely to be also present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enlargement of the right superficial inguinal lymph nodes","Dilatation of the veins of the Pampiniform plexus","A cough impulse at the right deep inguinal ring","Failure of transillumination of the swelling","Palpable para-aortic lymph nodes"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely cause of the swelling in the right side of his scrotum is a testicular tumour. There may be a hydrocele as a component to the swelling - but a primary hydrocele would be unusual in so young a patient. Part of the discipline of physical examination of any scrotal swelling is to see if the \u003Cstrong\u003Eswelling transilluminates\u003C/strong\u003E - ie is it a hydrocele? If the swelling is predominantly a tumour mass, it will not transilluminate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnother swelling that might lead to a failure of transillumination is an haematocele. In theory this patient could have sustained bruising and an haematocele when playing football three weeks earlier. However to sustain such an injury the event would have been extremely painful and the patient would almost certainly have sought immediate help and not waited three weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the tumour had already spread, it would have done so to the para-aortic and not the inguinal nodes. Unless they were massive, enlarged para-aortic nodes are not usually palpable. Dilatation of the veins of the Pampiniform plexus may make themselves evident as a soft swelling in the upper scrotum and this mass is known as a varicocele. Varicoceles have no relationship to testicular tumours. The presence of a cough impulse at the deep inguinal ring would be suggestive of an inguinal hernia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A solid enlargement of the testis in a young man is virtually diagnostic of a tumour.","It is not uncommon for testicular masses to be found post-trauma; self examination may have not been performed before."],"references":["Baird DC, Meyers GJ, Hu JS. Testicular Cancer: Diagnosis and Treatment. Am Fam Physician 2018; 97:261-68."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39961"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1084"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39961"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-05T07:32:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-05T07:32:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1084"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54452"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"grou